    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Abortion and Politics</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Melanie Quinn letter responds to July 21 letter that suggested Republican presidential candidate George W Bush demonstrate his respect for pro-choice Republicans by selecting pro-choice vice-presidential running mate (M)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A July 21 letter concludes that if George W. Bush is to respect the pro-choice members of his party by selecting a pro-choice running mate, as suggested in a July 19 editorial, by the same theory Al Gore should choose an anti-abortion running mate to respect the views of Democrats who are not pro-choice.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A July 21 letter concludes that if George W. Bush is to respect the pro-choice members of his party by selecting a pro-choice running mate, as suggested in a July 19 editorial, by the same theory Al Gore should choose an anti-abortion running mate to respect the views of Democrats who are not pro-choice.</p>
        <p>The vast majority of Americans want to keep abortion safe and legal. It is their views that deserve respect when considering a candidate for high national office.</p>
        <p>MELANIE QUINN  Park Ridge, N.J., July 21, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
